            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><em><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">DC.XVI.R1</span></em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">My Aunt&rsquo;s husband</span></strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri,sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Dickens's decision to have Betsey tell David the story of her marriage at at the end of a chapter that deals predominantly with Emily&rsquo;s discovery implicitly juxtaposes Emily&rsquo;s misplaced belief in Steerforth with Betsey&rsquo;s misplaced belief in the husband she once thought \"the soul of honour\" (DC 695). While Emily eventually overcomes Steerforth&rsquo;s influence, however, Betsey professes herself &ldquo;an incurable fool&rdquo; where her husband is concerned: &ldquo;for the sake of what I once believed him to be,&rdquo; she tells David, &ldquo;I wouldn&rsquo;t have even this shadow of my idle fancy hardly dealt with.&rdquo; </span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"
